title: For Sale:  Western Arms (A BRANCH OF ITHICA) 16 gauge double barrel
location: Bel Air,Harford County, Maryland, United States
postcontent:
28" barrels. marked"2" modified and "4" full choke . matching numbers on barrel and frame.smooth clean bore.double triggers.tight face with no wobble.walnut stocks with no cracks.
RESEARCH FROM INTERNET:serial number #32731 shows 1935 as date of manufacture.
 The Long Range Double was offered in 12-, 16-, and 20-gauges and .410-bore. The 12- and 20-gauges were all chambered for 2 3/4 inch shells. The original .410-bores were chambered for 2 1/2 inch shells and the 16-gauges for 2 9/16 inch shells. By 1934 the .410-bores got 3-inch chambers and the 16-gauges 2 3/4 inch. At various times during production, options of automatic ejectors, a single non-selective trigger, ivory sights, and a recoil pad were offered. The ejectors were not offered on the .410-bores in the 1931 price list, but this isn't mentioned in the 1933 to 1935 price lists, and the ejectors were discontinued by 1936. Production basically ended with the Ithaca factory conversion for wartime production in 1942, but a few hundred Long Range Doubles were assembled and sold in 1946. With the quality of  this gun it is my best price and a very good one. Try looking these up on gunbroker.com  I do not give a higher price and than lower it so you think you are getting a deal. You already are.

Up for sale/trade is an 8MM Mauser.

Had it in my collection for a while as a shooter, gun runs great and is in average condition
It is NOT an original German Mauser, the rifle was made on the same machines as German rifles Post WW2. After Germany was disarmed Poland received many of the machines and technicians that made the rifles. Poland continued to make them on unmarked receivers like this one. The bolt on mine is from an original German Mauser. The action and lock up are very strong and this would make an excellent starting point in a custom build.

Looking for $300 cash OBO, also open to trades so feel free to offer what you have.
BILL OF SALE IS REQUIRED.

Capacity: 5
Sights: Elevation adjustable rear / windage adjustable front
Stock: Walnut
Trigger Pull: 7-8lbs

title: For Sale:  Springfield M1A SOCOM II w/ custom Walnut stock - one of a kind! Price reduced.
postcontent:
This is my rifle. There are no others like it, and this one can be yours.

Most likely, you've never seen an M1A SOCOM II in a wood stock with the lower rail section intact before. There are several reasons why they aren't available that way, which I'll get into in a bit.

This rifle started life as a SOCOM 16. As you may or may not know - the ONLY difference between a SOCOM 16 and a SOCOM II is the VLTOR rail system, and the etched label on the operating rod. That's it. Every single other component is the exact same between the two models. Same internals, same trigger, same muzzle brake, same gas system, same sights - same everything.

I retrofitted this rifle with a factory VLTOR SOCOM II rail system, although I did not replace the operating rod - as that's literally just a laser etched label. So yeah - this IS a SOCOM II - but the operating rod is laser etched with the 16 label. Additionally, the heel stamp and sight markings have all been color-filled in white.

But that's obviously not what makes this M1A unique. I doubt you've ever seen a SOCOM II in a wood stock with the full VLTOR rail section in person - because you just can't get them that way. In fact, you don't even really see very many in pictures - because there just really aren't but a handful in existence. If you're an M1A fan, you know that that you can take pretty much any M1A action and drop it onto pretty much any M1A stock without issue...with the single exception of the SOCOM II.

That's because the SOCOM II's VLTOR rail system has a super beefy bracket that prevents a wood stock from bedding properly. Additionally, the rivets on the upper rail hit the stock slightly, and the entire lower rail won't even mount because it hits the stock well before it seats. This means that if you want a wood stock on your SOCOM II, you've got some woodworking to do - and this is what stops most people from doing it. It's not just a couple of minutes with a Dremel...it's a job.

This stock started as a Boyd's GI profile premium walnut stock. I performed some meticulous custom inletting to allow for the VLTOR bracket, and then also relieved some material to allow for the rail system, which included significant re-profiling for the lower rail section. I then hand-sanded the entire stock, and applied several coats of Danish Oil over the course of several days. I then applied several coats of hand-rubbed satin poly to provide some protection for the finish. It's got a really nice grain pattern, and just the slightest bit of tiger stripe towards the forward end.

I finished this off with a brand new set of all metal stock components, finished in satin black. I used a new set, as I wanted to retain the completeness of the original stock as well, for ease in switching it back and forth. The original SAI synthetic black stock (in perfect condition) is also included, and you can switch it back and forth in about 30 seconds.

The end result is a truly stunning one-of-a-kind piece of art. There's just something about the juxtaposition of the modern rails on the classic wood. It gets ooh's and ahh's every time I take it to the range, and it's an absolute joy to shoot. The photos speak for themselves, and additional photos are available upon request.

Round count is around 300 - absolutely fabulous condition.

Included:

(1) Springfield Armory M1A SOCOM II 7.62mm/.308 Rifle, in custom Boyd's Walnut stock
(1) Springfield Armory M1A black synthetic stock, with metal components
(5) 20-round Check-Mate industries magazines
(2) 20-round "Korean" magazines
(2) 20-round National Magazine magazines
(1) 10-round Springfield magazine
(1) 10-round HNR magazine
(6) MagPul magazine pulls
(1) Padded rifle case
(1) Original cardboard box, manuals, and documents

Armslist only allows three photos - many more hi-rez detailed photos available upon request.

Price reduced to $2100.00

I'm not looking for any trades at this time. Additionally, while I do need to sell this rifle to take care of a couple of things around the house, I'm absolutely NOT in any rush. I know what this rifle is worth, and I'm not giving it away - so please save the ridiculous low-ball offers for someone else.
